The paper discusses the memristive properties of living systems, specifically the acellular slime mould \emph{Physarum polycephalum}. This falls under the category of bio-electronics, which is a subfield of embedded systems (cs.ET). Additionally, the paper discusses the use of the slime mould as a self-growing bio-electronic circuit, which could fall under the category of neural networks (cs.NE) or robotics (cs.RO). The study also involves modelling the V-I curves of the slime mould, which could fall under the category of systems and control (cs.SY). Finally, the paper discusses the unique properties of the slime mould as an active memristor, which could fall under the category of biologically inspired computing (cs.BI).
